s |title=112th Congress: Bill Johnson, R-Ohio (6th District) |first=John |last=Bicknell |newspaper=[[Congressional Quarterly]] |date=November 3, 2010 |url=http://news.yahoo.com/s/cq/20101103/pl_cq_politics/politics000003758215 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1954|11|10}}\n| birth_place =[[Roseboro, North Carolina|Roseboro]], [[North Carolina]]\n<!--Military service-->\n|nickname =\n|allegiance = [[United States]]\n|branch = {{air force|United States}}\n|serviceyears = 1973\u20131999\n|rank = [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|25px]]\n|unit =\n|commands =\n|battles =\n|awards = [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]]<br>[[Commendation Medal|Air Force Commendation Medal]]<br>[[National Defense Service Medal]]\n}}\n\n'''William Leslie \"Bill\" Johnson''' (born November 10, 1954) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|OH|6}} since 2011. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\n{{BLP sources section|date=January 2016}}\n\nBorn in Roseboro, North Carolina in 1954,<ref name=CQ/> Johnson grew up on family farms.  He entered the [[United States Air Force]] in 1973, married  Wanda Florence Porter April 30, 1975.  They had 3 children, Joshua Daniel Johnson born 1976; Julie Florence Johnson born 1978 and Jessica Leslie Johnson born 1983. He retired as a Lieutenant Colonel after a military career of more than 26 years. He graduated ''summa cum laude'' from [[Troy University]] in [[Troy, Alabama]] in 1979, and he earned his Master\u2019s Degree from [[Georgia Tech]] in 1984. During his tenure in the U.S. Air Force, Johnson was recognized as a Distinguished Graduate from the Air Force Reserve Officer Training Corps, Squadron Officers School, and Air Command & Staff College. Bill is also a recipient of the Air Force Meritorious Service Medal, the Air Force Commendation Medal, and the National Defense Service Medal. As Director of the Air Force\u2019s Chief Information Officer Staff at U.S. Special Operations Command, Johnson worked directly with senior congressional and Secretary of Defense representatives, as well as top leaders within the various U.S. intelligence communities, to ensure America\u2019s Special Operations forces were adequately equipped to carry out critical national security missions.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Bill Johnson |publisher=Bill Johnson for Congress Campaign Website |url=http://www.billjohnsonleads.com/about.html |accessdate=2010-11-11 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111172421/http://www.billjohnsonleads.com/about.html |archivedate=11 November 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe co-founded Johnson-Schley Management Group, an [[information technology]] (IT) [[IT consulting|consulting company]] that increased revenues by more than 200% in just three years under his leadership. In 2003, he left the company to form J2 Business Solutions, where he provided executive level IT support as a [[defense contractor]] to the U.S. military. From 2006 to 2010, he served as [[Chief Information Officer]] of a global manufacturer of highly electronic components for the transportation industry.<ref>[http://billjohnson.house.gov/biography/ Bill Johnson Congressional biography]. Retrieved November 20, 2016.</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2010====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2010#District 6}}\n\nIn May 2010, Johnson defeated two primary opponents to earn the Republican nomination.<ref>{{Cite web| title =Wilson, Johnson win in 6th District| publisher = Marietta Times | date =2010-05-05| url =http://www.mariettatimes.com/page/content.detail/id/521619/Wilson--Johnson-win-in-6th-District.html?nav=5189| accessdate =2010-11-18 }}</ref> In the general election, Johnson won his bid by a 50\u201345%<ref name=\"PoliticoMargin\">[http://www.politico.com/2010/maps/#/House/2010/OH The 2010 Results Maps \u2013 POLITICO.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> margin against incumbent [[Charlie Wilson (Ohio politician)|Charlie Wilson]]. He began his term in the [[112th United States Congress]] on January 3, 2011.\n\n====2012====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2012#District 6}}\nIn November 2011, Wilson filed a rematch in the newly redrawn 6th District.<ref>http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/196335-former-rep-charlie-wilson-will-seek-rematch-in-ohio</ref> Johnson defeated Wilson once again in a heavily contested race 53% to 47%, and began his second term in January 2013.\n\n====2014====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2014#District 6}}\nIn 2014, Johnson faced off against heavily-recruited Democrat Jennifer Garrison, a former State Representative and lawyer from Marietta, Ohio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmoa1490.com/newsarticle/11500 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-02-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202174536/http://www.wmoa1490.com/newsarticle/11500 |archivedate=2015-02-02 |df= }}</ref> Johnson defeated Garrison handily 58% to 39% with Green Party candidate Dennis Lambert taking 3%.  Johnson began his third term in January 2015.\n\n====2016====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2016#District 6}}\nJohnson was re-elected to a fourth term in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2016|2016 general election]], defeating Democrat Michael Lorentz, the mayor of [[Belpre, Ohio]] by a margin of 71%-29%.<ref>[ 2016 Ohio House Election Results]</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nBill Johnson is a member of both the Conservative [[Republican Study Committee]] and the centrist [[Republican Main Street Partnership]].\n\nDuring the 112th Congress, Johnson's \"Veteran's Health Care Facilities Capital Improvement Act\" was passed into law.<ref>{{cite web|title=Library of Congress \u2013 Thomas|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/D?d112:6:./temp/~bdIRSz::{{!}}/bss/|}}</ref>   Additionally, the House passed Johnson's \"World War II Memorial Prayer Act\" which would require the prayer President Franklin Roosevelt gave on D-Day to be placed on the World War II memorial.<ref>{{cite web|title=Library of Congress \u2013 Thomas|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/D?d112:2:./temp/~bdcbnv::{{!}}/bss/|}}</ref>  The House also passed Johnson's \"Stop the War on Coal Act\" which would stop the creation of any new rules that threaten mining jobs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Library of Congress \u2013 Thomas|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/D?d112:8:./temp/~bdTwmh:@@@D&summ2=m&{{!}}/bss/|}}</ref> Both pieces of legislation have been sent to the Senate for consideration.\n\nJohnson is also the sponsor of H.R. 4036,  the \"Pass a Budget Now Act\" which would cut the pay of legislators if a budget is not passed by April 15 of each year.<ref>{{cite web|title=GovTrack.us|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr4036}}</ref>\n\n;Abortion\nIn the 2010 Ohio Primary Election Candidate Survey, Johnson stated, \"I am pro-life, and I oppose abortion except in the case of rape, incest, and when the mother's life is in danger. Additionally, I support parental notification and a ban on partial birth abortions.\" During his 2010 and 2012 general elections, Johnson received the endorsement of the Ohio Right to Life PAC.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ohio Right to Life|url=http://www.ohiovotesforlife.org/endorsements/}}</ref>\n\n;Gun Issues\nA lifelong member of the [[National Rifle Association]], Johnson opposes restrictions on gun ownership.  He was endorsed by the NRA in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=NRA endorsements-Ohio|url=http://www.nrapvf.org/grades-endorsements/2012/ohio.aspx}}</ref>\n\n;Health care\nJohnson opposes the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\n;Gay Marriage\nJohnson opposes the legalization of gay marriage and believes that it \u201cundermines the integrity of the American family.\u201d <ref>{{cite web | title = Bill Johnson: Issue Positions | publisher = Project Vote Smart | url = http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/120649/bill-johnson/ | accessdate = 2011-11-20}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade|Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing, and Trade]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Environment and Economy|Subcommittee on Environment and Economy]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space]]\n\n===Legislation sponsored===\n* [[Community Fire Safety Act of 2013 (H.R. 3588; 113th Congress)]] \u2013 Johnson introduced this bill into the House on November 21, 2013.<ref name=3588sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3588 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th/house-bill/3588|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref> The bill would prevent the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] from requiring that all new [[fire hydrant]]s in the United States be [[lead]]-free beginning in 2014.<ref name=bothpartiesreject>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=Both parties reject EPA fire hydrant rule|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/votes/191828-gop-dems-reject-epa-rule-on-fire-hydrants|accessdate=3 December 2013|newspaper=The Hill|date=2 December 2013}}</ref> Johnson referred to the EPA's ruling as \"absurd\" and said that \"it is unconscionable that the EPA has put our public safety at risk because during the hot summer months sometimes, somewhere kids may play in fire hydrant water.\"<ref name=epathreat1>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House bill warns of EPA threat to fire hydrants|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/energyenvironment/191208-members-look-to-block-epa-rule-requiring-lead-free-fire|accessdate=3 December 2013|newspaper=The Hill|date=22 November 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Preventing Government Waste and Protecting Coal Mining Jobs in America (H.R. 2824; 113th Congress)]] \u2013 Johnson introduced this bill into the House on July 25, 2013.<ref name=2824allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 2824 \u2013 All Actions|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/2824/all-actions/|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref> If passed, the bill would amend the [[Surface Mining Control and Reclamation Act of 1977]] to require state programs for regulation of [[Surface mining|surface coal mining]] to incorporate the necessary rule concerning excess spoil, coal mine waste, and buffers for perennial and intermittent streams published by the Office of Surface Mining Reclamation and Enforcement on December 12, 2008.<ref name=2824sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 2824 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/2824|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Supporters of the bill argue that it will be good for jobs, save the government money, and improve U.S. energy production by  preventing the Obama Administration from introducing more coal regulations.<ref name=SmartEnergy>{{cite web|title=Johnson, Lamborn Introduce Legislation To Protect Jobs, Help Stop Administration\u2019s War on Coal|url=http://www.smartenergyuniverse.com/regulatory/19688-johnson-lamborn-introduce-legislation-to-protect-jobs-help-stop-administration-s-war-on-coal|publisher=Smart Energy Universe|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=3 March 2014}}</ref> Opponents of the bill described it as a bill that would require \"OSM to implement the flawed 2008 Stream Buffer Zone rule and prevent the agency from improving that rule for a minimum of seven years.\"<ref name=EcoWatchBeans>{{cite news|last=Beans|first=Laura|title=House Republicans Use Fear Mongering In Fight for Mountaintop Removal Coal Mining|url=http://ecowatch.com/2013/08/08/republicans-fight-for-mountaintop-removal-coal-mining/|accessdate=5 March 2014|newspaper=EcoWatch|date=8 August 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Improving Trauma Care Act of 2014 (H.R. 3548; 113th Congress)]] \u2013 Johnson introduced this bill into the House on November 20, 2013.<ref name=3548sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3548 \u2013 Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3548|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref> It is a bill that would amend the [[Public Health Service Act]], with respect to trauma care and research programs, to include in the definition of \"trauma\" an [[injury]] resulting from extrinsic agents other than mechanical force, including those that are thermal, electrical, chemical, or radioactive.<ref name=\"3548sum\"/>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{|class=\"wikitable collapsible\"\n|-bgcolor=#cccccc\n!colspan=24 style=\"background: #ccccff;\" |Election results<ref>{{cite news | first = | last =  | title = Election Results | date = | url = http://www.sos.state.oh.us/elections/Research/electResultsMain.aspx | work = Ohio Secretary of State | accessdate = 2016-12-04}}</ref>\n|-\n!'''Year'''\n!'''Office'''\n!'''Election'''\n!\n!'''Name'''\n!'''Party'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!\n!'''Opponent'''\n!'''Party'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!\n!'''Opponent'''\n!'''Party'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!\n!'''Opponent'''\n!'''Party'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!\n|-\n|2010\n|[[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]\n|[[General election (U.S.)|General]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Bill Johnson'''\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |[[Republican Party (United States)|Repu